			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Pull Spliting<a name="72574"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 27 05 11:08 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>One way of getting one mob to split is to hit it with a mez and have someone from the group tag it while you're keeping the others busy. Be careful not to get too far away from the group though, or no one will get experience for the kill. You can also do this with single target snare when you get it, but that's not for a while.
<br />

<br />
This brings up a very important skill that you need to learn. Crowd control. Bards use our CC techniques to make impossible pulls look flawless, as pure CC when there's no chanter or when the chanter is overtaxed, and as a soloing tactic. You can keep 3-4 mobs mezzed, depending on resists, without too much trouble (at least in the lower levels). Sure, you're not adding in the melee damage or buffing the group, but you're preventing a wipe. 
<br />

<br />
One tactic to get used to when doing CC is the melee/switch/mez/switch/melee method. You can actually melee and keep another mob mezzed. Make sure you have a &quot;toggle last 2 targets&quot; key set up. Melee as usual (I usually only twist my 2 most important songs when doing this) and every time you get to your mez song in the twist, tap that key real quick before starting the song. As soon as it starts casting, tap that key again and continue meleeing. The song hits the target you have selected WHEN THE SONG STARTS CASTING. This will allow you to maximize your DPS and group buffs, while still keeping a mob locked down.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1003866"> <img src="http://everquest.allakhazam.com/uf/Jiggidyjay/zingsig.jpg"></a></br><fontsize=8>Zingin Ansinging, Povar</fontsize></span></td>
